::: {.cell} ::: First, you must always load the [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} library in your R script or Quarto document. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(Pmetrics) ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â„¹ Loading Pmetrics ``` ::: ::: # Running NPAG ### Working directory Next, R and [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} need to know which directory to work in. This is the directory where R expects to find files and where it will save output files. There are two ways to do this. #### Global working directory change You can set your working directory with the [`setwd`](https://rdrr.io/pkg/base/man/getwd.html) function. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} setwd("/path/to/your/project/directory") # Mac and Linux users setwd("C:/path/to/your/project/directory") # Windows users ``` ::: **Windows users:** Make sure that you separate directories with a forward slash "/" or double backslashes "\\". Unfortunately, Windows is the only OS that uses backslashes "", so R conforms to Unix/Linux style with the forward slash. If you copy the example below, make sure to change the path to one that exists on your computer. #### Local path specification You can also specify the path in a variable and use it in [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} functions without changing the working directory. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} wd <- "/path/to/your/project/directory" # Mac and Linux users wd <- "C:/path/to/your/project/directory" # Windows users dat <- PM_data$new(data = file.path(wd, "data", "mydata.csv")) ``` ::: ðŸ’¡ The [`file.path`](https://rdrr.io/pkg/base/man/file.path.html) function creates file paths that are compatible with your operating system. ### Workflow The typical workflow for using [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} is as follows: 1. Create a [`PM_data`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_data.html) object. 2. Create a [`PM_model`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_model.html) object. 3. Fit the model to the data with the `$fit()` method of the model object. This returns a [`PM_result`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_result.html) object, which is also saved to the hard drive and can be loaded later with the [`PM_load`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_load.html) function. 4. Examine the results with [`PM_result`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_result.html) methods and functions and revise as needed to improve the model fit. This chiefly means using the `$update()` method to change the model or manually editing it. ```{mermaid} %%| eval: true flowchart LR subgraph RSession[" "] direction TB DATA["PM_data"] MODEL["PM_model"] RESULT["PM_result"] end DISK[("Hard Drive")] DATA --> MODEL MODEL -- "$fit()" --> RESULT RESULT -- "$update()" --> MODEL DISK -- "PM_load()" --> RESULT RESULT --> DISK classDef blue fill:#2f6db6,stroke:#184a8b,color:#fff; classDef orange fill:#c7662b,stroke:#8a3f18,color:#fff; classDef disk fill:#d2d3d7,stroke:#7f8084,color:#000; class DATA,MODEL blue; class RESULT orange; class DISK disk; style RSession fill:#e9f0ff,stroke:#9ab0d6,stroke-width:1px,rx:2,ry:2 ``` ### Data objects Pmetrics always needs data and a model to run, so let's create a new data object. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} exData <- PM_data$new(data = "../Examples/src/ex.csv") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”€â”€ DATA STANDARDIZATION â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` EVID inferred as 0 for observations, 1 for doses. All doses assumed to be oral (DUR = 0). ADDL set to missing for all records. II set to missing for all records. All doses assumed to be INPUT = 1. All observations assumed to be OUTEQ = 1. All observations assumed to be uncensored. One or more error coefficients not specified. Error in model object will be used. ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` â”€â”€ DATA VALIDATION â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` No data errors found. ``` ::: ::: [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} standardizes the data, checks for errors, and provides an error and attempted fix report fo any found. You can look at a .csv data file directly by opening it in a spreadsheet program like Excel, or a text editor. `exData` is an [`R6`](https://rdrr.io/pkg/R6/man/R6Class.html) object, which means that contains both data and methods to process that data. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} exData # prints the object, usually to the terminal, but in this case to a rendered "lite" spreadsheet exData$data # contains your original data exData$standard_data # contains the standardized and validated data exData$summary() # prints the summary of the data to the terminal ``` ::: Most [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} objects are R6 objects, so you can use the `$` operator to access their data and methods. Many of them have a `summary()` method that prints a summary of the object to the console and a `plot()` method that creates a plot of the object. See [`PM_data`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_data.html) for more information on the `PM_data` class and its methods. **Note:** We recognize that many users are familiar with the "S3 framework" in R, which uses functions like `summary(object)` and `plot(object)`. To comply with better programming standards, [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} uses the R6 framework. However, we have provided S3 methods for most functions, so you can use `summary(object)` and `plot(object)` if you prefer. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # S3 method to summarize data summary(exData) ``` ::: `PM_data` has a `plot()` method that creates a plot of the data. See [`plot.PM_data`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/plot.PM_data.html) for more information. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} exData$plot() ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ### Model objects You can specify a model by reading a file or directly as a list object in R. We'll do both. The following code creates the same model as in `/src/model.txt` file. See further [model details](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/articles/models.html) on creating models in R compared to text files. The advantage of creating them in R is that one does not need to copy model files into folders to provide necessary inputs. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mod1 <- PM_model$new( pri = list( Ka = ab(0.1, 0.9), Ke = ab(0.001, 0.1), V = ab(30, 120), lag1 = ab(0, 4) ), cov = list( wt = interp(), africa = interp("none"), age = interp(), gender = interp("none"), height = interp() ), eqn = function(){ two_comp_bolus }, lag = function(){ lag[1] = lag1 }, out = function(){ Y[1] = X[2]/V }, err = list( proportional(5, c(0.02, 0.05, -0.0002, 0)) ) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output {.cell-output-display} ![](NPAG_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: We have another file "model.txt" that contains the old representation of the same model we coded above, let's take a look at it. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} system("cat ../Examples/src/model.txt") ``` ::: You can also open it in a text editor. `PM_model$new()` also accepts the path to a model file to create the same model using the file. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mod1b <- PM_model$new("../Examples/src/model.txt") mod1b # look at it ``` ::: PM_model provides a method to update the different elements of a model, for example: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mod1b$update( pri = list( ka = ab(0.001, 5) )) ``` ::: It is case sensitive, so ka is different from Ka. To remove a parameter, set it to NULL. To copy a model use the `$clone()` method. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mod1b <- mod1$clone() ``` ::: Simply using `mod1b <- mod1` will cause `mod1b` to be changed if `mod1` is changed, as R6 objects use reference semantics. For more details you can refer to [Advanced R](https://adv-r.hadley.nz/r6.html), Section 14.4. Lastly, [Pmetrics]{style="color: #841010; font-family: 'Arial', Arial, sans-serif; font-weight: 900;"} has a model building app! ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} build_model() #start from scratch build_model(exData) #start with data to match covariates build_model(mod1) #start with a model and update it ``` ::: ### Fit the model to the data To keep everything tidy, we are working in a folder specifically to store the runs. We are specifying the path in the call to `$fit()` rather than globally changing the working directory. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} run1 <- mod1$fit(data = exData, run = 1, overwrite = TRUE, path = "../Examples/Runs") ``` ::: The [`PM_model`](https://lapkb.github.io/Pmetrics/reference/PM_model.html) class has a `$fit()` method that fits the model to the data. ::: {.cell} ::: After the run is complete the results are returned to the assigned object, here 'run1'. However, if you want to load the results later, you can use the `PM_load()` function. Runs will be sequentially numbered as /1, /2, /3,... in your working directory. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} run1 <- PM_load(1, path = "../Examples/Runs") # load the results from run 1 if returning to this script later ``` :::
